Types of Segmentation fault

1.	Dereferencing null or uninitialized pointers:
	
	int *ptr = NULL;
	*ptr = 10; // Segmentation fault --> assigning value to a memory location pointed to by NULL

Valgrind Error:
	Invalid write of size 4
	Process terminating with default action of signal 11 (SIGSEGV)
	Access not within mapped region at address 0x0
Why size 4?
4 bytes. i.e 1 x integer

2.	Accessing out-of-bounds array elements:

	int arr[5];
	arr[10] = 7; // Segmentation fault

Valgrind Error:
	Jump to the invalid address	
	Address 0x7 is not stack'd, malloc'd or (recently) free'd

3.	Buffer overflows:
	char buf[10];
	strcpy(buf, "This is a long string"); // Segmentation fault

Valgrind:
	although this is expected to give valgrind error.
	it didn't throw any error.

4.	Using freed or deallocated memory:
	
	int *ptr = malloc(sizeof(int));
	free(ptr);
	*ptr = 10; // Segmentation fault

Valgrind Error:
	Invalid write of size 4
	Address 0x4a9d040 is 0 bytes inside a block of size 4 free'd

5.	Stack overflow:
	void recurse() 
	{
    		recurse(); // Segmentation fault due to stack overflow
	}

Valgrind Error:
	Stack overflow in thread #1: can't grow stack to 0x1ffe801000
	Process terminating with default action of signal 11 (SIGSEGV)
	Access not within mapped region at address 0x1FFE801FF8

6.	Writing to read-only memory:
	
	 // String literals are usually stored in read-only memory
    	char *str = "Hello, World!";
    	str[0] = 'h'; // Attempt to modify read-only memory
    	
Valgrind Error:
	Process terminating with default action of signal 11 (SIGSEGV)
	Bad permissions for mapped region at address 0x402004

7.	Incorrect pointer arithmetic:

	int arr[5];
	int *ptr = arr + 10;			--> ptr is pointing to out of range array index
	*ptr = 5; // Segmentation fault

Valgrind Error:
	Jump to the invalid address
	Process terminating with default action of signal 11 (SIGSEGV)

	HEAP SUMMARY: 
	total heap usage: 1 allocs, 0 frees, 1,024 bytes allocated
Why does it say 0 frees, when I have not dynamically allocated anything? 
Some standard library functions and I/O operations might perform dynamic memory allocations internally. 
This can cause Valgrind to report these allocations in the heap summary.

Because Segmentation fault occured at a certain line, SIGSEGV signal was sent, program exited abruptly, 
it couldn't do the internal memory cleanup.

